    <section id="products">
      <h2>4. Products &amp; Services</h2>
      <p><strong>Descriptions:</strong> Roll-off dumpster rental and hauling. Containers are delivered to and removed from job sites for new construction, renovation/remodel, and residential/commercial clean-out. Operates multiple roll-off trucks and a ~186-unit container fleet.</p>
      <p><strong>Pricing model:</strong> Per-rental / per-haul, priced by container size, debris type, duration, and distance. Orlando 2026 roll-off pricing runs ~$300–$800 per rental (10–40 yard). Revenue is transactional, not contracted, though repeat behavior is very high. Raising prices is a flagged growth lever.</p>
      <p><strong>Differentiators:</strong> ~26-year local tenure and brand; a ~100% gross-profit service model; modern dispatch software enabling lean operations; a referral engine (95% of new clients) holding CAC near zero; an owned ~186-unit container fleet that is a barrier to entry.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="market">
      <h2>5. Market Analysis</h2>
      <p><strong>Industry size &amp; trends:</strong> The U.S. dumpster rental industry is ~$542.5M in 2025, growing at a ~5.7% five-year CAGR (IBISWorld), ~7.2% in 2025 alone. Demand is driven by construction, housing, infrastructure spending, disaster recovery, and renovation. The industry is highly fragmented — ~232 operators nationally — which is what makes it a roll-up target.</p>
      <p><strong>Drivers:</strong> Orlando is the fastest-growing large U.S. metro; Central Florida construction starts keep climbing in 2026 (~$15.6B new contracts; residential ~$8.75B, non-residential ~$4.6B). Megaprojects (Disney's $17B expansion, Universal's Epic Universe, I-4 Ultimate, downtown redevelopment) sustain construction-debris demand. <strong>Barriers:</strong> Rising landfill tipping fees compress margins; truck/container capex; driver labor scarcity; construction-cycle and interest-rate sensitivity.</p>
      <p><strong>Competitive landscape:</strong> National independents trade at 2.5x–4.5x SDE for sub-$1M-SDE operators — this listing at 3.47x is mid-range. Orlando is a crowded local field (Coast To Coast Disposal, Orlando Dumpster Company, Javi's Dumpster Rental, Dumpster Medic). PE-backed consolidators are actively rolling up roll-off operators nationally; mid-size platforms command 5x+ EBITDA — a multiple-arbitrage opportunity for a buyer who consolidates small operators at 3–4x.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="customers">
      <h2>6. Customers &amp; Revenue Model</h2>
      <p><strong>Segments:</strong> B2B and B2C mix — general/trade contractors (construction), homeowners and remodelers (renovation), property owners/managers and estate clean-out clients. Concentrated in the Orlando metro.</p>
      <p><strong>Retention:</strong> No churn % disclosed. Listing claims 99% repeat business — a strong loyalty signal, though "repeat" in transactional hauling is not contracted recurring revenue.</p>
      <p><strong>Recurring vs one-time:</strong> Effectively 0% contracted recurring; revenue is transactional per-haul. But 99% repeat + 95% referral-sourced new clients makes aggregate revenue sticky and predictable.</p>
      <p><strong>Top customer concentration:</strong> Not disclosed. The referral-and-repeat profile across three demand streams implies a diffuse base with no dominant account — but this MUST be confirmed; a hidden GC concentration would change the risk profile.</p>
    </section>

